{
  "local_port": 32980,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I re-apply for an H1B after cancelled without prejudice?",
  "response": "If your H1B petition was canceled \"without prejudice,\" it means that the U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) did not issue a final decision on your case and did not prevent you from applying again. This presents an opportunity to reapply for an H1B visa. Here\u2019s the step-by-step process to re-apply:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Understand the Reason for Cancellation**\n   - Review the notice of cancellation to understand why your H1B petition was canceled. Common reasons include incomplete documentation, errors, or procedural issues.\n   - Address the issue(s) that led to the cancellation to avoid recurrence in your new application.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Secure a New Job Offer (If Needed)**\n   - Ensure that your prospective U.S. employer is willing to sponsor your H1B petition again. The employer must file the H1B petition on your behalf.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Check H1B Cap Availability**\n   - If you are subject to the H1B cap (i.e., not cap-exempt), confirm whether you need to participate in the H1B lottery again. Note that a canceled petition does not count as a selected or approved petition.\n   - If you previously were selected in the lottery but your petition was canceled, you may need to re-enter the lottery process.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Prepare the H1B Petition**\n   - Work with your employer and immigration attorney to prepare a complete and accurate H1B petition. This includes:\n     - Form I-129 (Petition for a Nonimmigrant Worker)\n     - Labor Condition Application (LCA) certified by the Department of Labor (DOL)\n     - Supporting documents (e.g., job offer letter, educational credentials, resume, etc.)\n   - Double-check all forms and documents to ensure they meet USCIS requirements.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Submit the Petition**\n   - File the H1B petition with USCIS during the appropriate filing period (e.g., during the cap season or anytime for cap-exempt positions).\n   - Pay the required filing fees.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Monitor the Application**\n   - Track the status of your petition using the receipt number provided by USCIS.\n   - Respond promptly to any Requests for Evidence (RFEs) if USCIS asks for additional information.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Attend Visa Interview (If Outside the U.S.)**\n   - If your H1B petition is approved and you are outside the U.S., schedule a visa interview at the U.S. embassy or consulate in your home country.\n   - Prepare the required documents for the interview, including the approval notice (Form I-797).\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Enter the U.S.**\n   - Once your visa is approved, you can enter the U.S. and begin working for your employer under the H1B status.\n\n---\n\n### Additional Notes:\n- If your H1B was canceled while you were in the U.S., ensure your legal status is maintained or transitioned appropriately (e.g., by applying for a change of status or leaving the U.S. before your authorized stay expires).\n- Consulting an experienced immigration attorney is highly recommended to navigate the process smoothly and minimize the risk of errors.\n\nBy addressing the reasons for the initial cancellation and submitting a strong, complete petition, you increase your chances of securing an H1B visa.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
